03787nam a22006735i 9780674262492DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20221997mau    fo  d z      eng d  a9780674262492  a(DE-B1597)586307  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aRC552.A44bC37 1995 7aPSY0220602bisacsh04a616.85/2252201 aCapps, Lisa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aConstructing Panic :bThe Discourse of Agoraphobia /cLisa Capps, Elinor Ochs. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©1997  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMeg Logan has not been farther than two miles from home in six years. She has agoraphobia, a debilitating anxiety disorder that entraps its sufferers in the fear of leaving safe havens such as home. Paradoxically, while at this safe haven, agoraphobics spend much of their time ruminating over past panic experiences and imagining similar hypothetical situations. In doing so, they create a narrative that both describes their experience and locks them into it. Constructing Panic offers an unprecedented analysis of one patient's experience of agoraphobia. In this novel interdisciplinary collaboration between a clinical psychologist and a linguist, the authors probe Meg's stories for constructions of emotions, actions, and events. They illustrate how Meg uses grammar and narrative structure to create and recreate emotional experiences that maintain her agoraphobic identity. In this work Capps and Ochs propose a startling new view of agoraphobia as a communicative disorder. Constructing Panic opens up the largely overlooked potential for linguistic and narrative analysis by revealing the roots of panic and by offering a unique framework for therapeutic intervention. Readers will find in these pages hope for managing panic through careful attention to how we tell the story of our lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAgoraphobiavCase studies. 0aDiscourse analysis, Narrative. 0aDiscourse analysis. 0aPanic attacks. 0aPersonal construct theory. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Psychopathology / Anxieties & Phobias.2bisacsh1 aBruner, Jerome, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOchs, Elinor, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z978311044221240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674262492423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674262492/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK